<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Sat, 14 Sep 2002 11:23:20 -0400
From: Omar Shafey <Omar.Shafey@cancer.org>
Source: Kathmandu Post [edited]
<http://www.nepalnews.com.np/contents/englishdaily/ktmpost/2002/sep/sep14/index.htm#3>

This report [below] mentions 15 deaths and 100 cases of illness attributed
to an infectious disease outbreak of unknown etiology in Dolakha district,
Nepal.
Dolakha district is 130 kilometers northeast of Kathmandu in a remote
Himalayan region wracked by 6 years of guerilla warfare. The Bangkok-based
US Armed Forces Research Institute of Medical Sciences currently conducts
influenza surveillance in Nepal so perhaps their resources will be
mobilized to assist the Nepali government's response to this outbreak.

Strange disease kills 15 in Dolakha
Peon [guardian/keeper] decides fate of 100 others
---------------
13 Sep 2002: At least 15 people, including 2 children died immediately
after showing signs of headache, fever and running nose in Jhyaku VDC. The
epidemic has spread like a wildfire and infected another 100 in less than 2
weeks. The unknown disease threatens to engulf the whole of Jhyaku village.
The only staff at the village health post is a peon [guardian/keeper].
Records of the exact dead patients are unavailable. However, sounding
alarm, the District Health Office in Dolakha said at least 15 have died of
an "unknown disease". The response of the District Health Office comes only
on Friday, 2 weeks after the epidemic killed 15 people and infected 100 others.
Counting his fingers, Netra Jirel, a peon guarding over the Jhayku-based
health post said, at least 15 people are daily reporting at the health post
complaining of sickness. Jirel is the only person in the health post
handling a large number of incoming patients but is unable to write the
names of the patients without the aid of a literate person. Due to the
absence of a person to register the names of the patients, an exact death
toll is yet to be ascertained.
According to CDO Daya Ram Sharma, he has immediately acted upon receiving
the news of the spread of disease. "We will soon be sending a medical team
to Jhyaku VDC."
Former VDC chairman Narendra Pathak told The Kathmandu Post today that
wards-1, 2, 5, 6, 7 and 8 have been affected in the last few days. "Since
the last 2 months, health post in the region has simply a peon to handle
everything and has no medical staff, let alone doctors to diagnose the
increasing number of patients."
"The health post has hardly any medicine, which has further complicated the
matter. There is an urgent need to send a medical team here," he said.
However, technician Krishna Mijar at the District Health Office in Dolakha
claimed that he had sent some antibiotics through Jirel to tackle the
problem. But for a health post without a single medical practitioner to
prescribe the tablets, it is up to the peon, Jirel, to ultimately decide
the life and death of the innocent people.
--
Omar Shafey, Ph.D., M.P.H.
Manager, International Tobacco Surveillance
American Cancer Society
Atlanta, GA 30329-4251 USA
<Omar.Shafey@cancer.org>
