[2]
Date: 14 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Company 14 Sep 2002 20:53 AEDT [edited]
<http://abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s676348.htm>

15 dead as mystery illness baffles Nepal's doctors
--------------------------
Nepal has sent doctors to a village in the kingdom's northeast, where 15
people have died and 100 others have fallen sick from an illness that is
baffling medical authorities.
In the past 2 weeks, 15 people, including 2 children, have died in the
village of Jhyaku in Dolakha district, about 90 kilometres north-east of
Kathmandu. Symptoms of the malady include a headache, fever and runny nose.
Officials fear the illness could be contagious and spread across the region.
"District health officials could not diagnose the nature of the disease but
medical experts have been dispatched," an official in Nepal's Health
Ministry said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The description of illness given above seems consistent with an
influenza-like illness (given the mention of "runny nose" as part of the
clinical spectrum of disease), and the scarcity of health care personnel
and medicines would be consistent with an observed higher mortality
resulting from secondary untreated bacterial pneumonia, in a possibly
marginally nourished population (reminiscent of the higher mortality
related to an influenza outbreak in Madagascar this year). In 1996 there
was a similar thread in ProMED-mail, starting as a "mystery illness"
reported in western Nepal, which ultimately was evaluated to be the usual
and expected ARI (acute respiratory illness) outbreak seen seasonally in
Nepal -- the season identified as December through April. In contrast,
Nepal is endemic/epidemic for Japanese encephalitis, with annual outbreaks
in the rainy season June- September, the current season. The news reports
above seem to suggest that adults are the primary fatalities (only 2/15
deaths were in children), another curiosity/anomaly proposing a
differential diagnosis (such as measles, which can present with an upper
respiratory component). In the past we have been fortunate that officials
working within the health sector in Nepal have responded to our requests
fairly rapidly when information becomes available. We would very much
appreciate information on this current outbreak from official sources. -
Mod.MPP]
